  "prompt": "How is the concentration of concentrated HCl calculated?",
  "response": "The concentration of concentrated HCl (hydrochloric acid) is typically expressed in several ways:\n\n1. Percent Purity (w/w or w/v)\n- Indicates the weight of pure HCl per 100 grams or 100 mL of solution\n- Common concentrated HCl is around 37% w/w\n- Represents the mass percentage of pure HCl\n\n2. Molarity (M)\n- Moles of HCl per liter of solution\n- Concentrated HCl is typically around 12 M\n- Calculated by: Molarity = (Percent purity \u00d7 Density) \u00f7 (Molar mass)\n\n3. Normality (N)\n- Equivalents of HCl per liter of solution\n- Depends on the acid's hydrogen ion contribution\n\nCalculation steps:\n- Know the percent purity\n- Measure solution density\n- Use molar mass of HCl (36.46 g/mol)\n- Apply appropriate conversion formulas\n\nFactors affecting concentration:\n- Manufacturing process\n- Dilution\n- Temperature\n- Purity of original acid\n\nAlways verify concentration through precise laboratory measurements.",
